jacqueline barton  wikipedia jacqueline barton from wikipedia the free encyclopedia jump to navigation search jacqueline barton jacqueline barton aic gold medal  born jacqueline k barton new york city nationality usa fields chemistry institutions bell labs yale university hunter college columbia university california institute of technology alma mater barnard college columbia university doctoral advisor sj lippardcitation needed doctoral students duncan odom notable awards nsf waterman award  acs award in pure chemistry  macarthur foundation fellow  garvan–olin medal  weizmann women  science award  acs gibbs medal  linus pauling award  national medal of science  aic gold medal  priestley medal  website wwwitscaltechedujkbgrpbartonbiographyhtm jacqueline k barton born new york city ny is an american chemist she worked as a professor of chemistry at hunter college – and at columbia university – before joining the california institute of technology to the present in  she became the arthur and marian hanisch memorial professor of chemistry and in  the chair of the division of chemistry and chemical engineering at caltech she currently is the john g kirkwood and arthur a noyes professor and norman davidson leadership chair of the division of chemistry and chemical engineering barton studies the chemical and physical properties of dna and their roles in biological activities the primary focus of her research is transverse electron transport along doublestranded dna its implications in the biology of dna damage and repair and its potential for materials sciences applications such as targeted chemotherapeutic treatments for cancer among many other awards barton has received the  national medal of science the  american institute of chemists gold medal and the  priestley medal contents  education  career and research  research summary  awards and honors  references educationedit jacqueline kapelman attended riverdale country school for girls in riverdale new york where her math teacher mrs rosenberg insisted that she be allowed to take calculus at the boys school her interest in chemistry began at barnard college where she studied physical chemistry with bernice segal she loved laboratory work and chemical transformations and found segal an inspiration as a teacher during her last year at barnard she married don barton receiving her ba from barnard college as jacqueline kapelman barton summa cum laude in  she then studied inorganic chemistry at columbia university under the supervision of stephen j lippard while at columbia she began studying transitionmetal complexes and their possible applications to chemotherapy she earned a phd in inorganic chemistry in  addressing the structure and chemical reactivity of a blue platinum complex  the interaction of antitumor latinum drugs and matallointercalation reagent with nucleic acids career and researchedit external media audio nature uses this for longrange signalling and finding mistakes in dna jacqueline barton dna like wire for signaling within a cell earthsky  chemical heritage foundation video science is the most fun in the whole wide world medal of science  videos  peter dervan and jacqueline barton national science foundation after earning her phd from columbia in  barton held postdoctoral appointments at bell labs and yale university where she worked with robert g shulman she used nuclear magnetic resonance imaging technology to examine the metabolism of yeast cells barton became a professor of chemistry at hunter college from – and began to develop her own laboratory the barton research group while at hunter she studied the interactions of zinc ions with dna and later of rutheniumii and cobaltiii complexes with dna this enabled her to roughly model complexes on a dna helix and to begin studying the photophysical and photochemical properties related to enantiomers in the s she moved to columbia university where she taught from  to  she became a full professor in  and was the first woman to receive tenure in the chemistry department at columbia her research focused on the use of organoruthenium complexes to examine the physical structure of dna with nicholas turro and vijay kumar she studied the interactions of ruthenium phenanthroline complexes and dna and was able to design binding molecules targeted to specific dna sequences photosensitive ruthenium complexes would glow brightly when they attached to the dna double helix when rhodium complexes were attached to the dna they would attract the electron causing the glow and turn off the effect during her time at columbia barton obtained two patents for this method of analyzing dna structure in  barton moved to caltech where her research has focused on charge transport in dna by using speciallydesigned chiral metal complexes as probes of dna she has been able to study how dna is damaged and repaired in dnabased diagnostic tests complexes are used to determine whether electrons can flow across the dna if an electron could not move along the dna the dna would continue to glow indicating that there was damage in the dna genetic molecule the research that barton catherine j murphy megan núñez and others have done at caltech has supported the idea of fast longrange electron transfer over dna challenging accepted scientific views and causing considerable controversy based on years of studies barton and her group theorize that dna operates like a wire supporting a type of longrange signaling that enables repair proteins to detect and correct mistakes in dna this view of dna is deeper and more dynamic than previous views of dna as a static library understanding the mediation of electrontransfer chemistry by the dna double helix has laid a foundation for the development of new diagnostic tools and for the possible design of novel chemotherapeutics barton erik holmlin shana kelley and mike hill created the company geneohm sciences to explore the development of sensitive diagnostics for detecting dna mismatches the company has since been acquired by bd diagnostics barton has taught more than  graduate and postdoctoral students many of whom are women recognized as a superb role model not just for young women but for all young scientists barton advises others that the best thing that i can do for women in science is first to do good science she became the arthur and marian hanisch memorial professor of chemistry in  she was named chair of the division of chemistry and chemical engineering of california institute of technology effective july   barton has been a member of the board of dow chemical since  she has also served on the gilead sciences scientific advisory board  in  she married peter dervan a fellow chemist and professor at caltech who is also a national medal of science winner she has two children a daughter elizabeth and a stepson andrew research summaryedit barton third right receiving the national medal of science at the white house in  barton introduced the application of transition metal complexes to probe recognition and reactions of double helical dna she has designed chiral metal complexes which mimic the properties of dnabinding proteins allowing other researchers the capability to simulate and analyze experiments in this nature barton additionally established that dna charge transport chemistry is extremely sensitive to intervening perturbations in the dna base stack as with single base mismatches or lesions this discovery has been a cornerstone for the development of dnabased electrochemical sensors awards and honorsedit barton was awarded the national medal of science by barack obama in  for discovery of a new property of the dna helix longrange electron transfer and for showing that electron transfer depends upon stacking of the base pairs and dna dynamics her experiments reveal a strategy for how dna repair proteins locate dna lesions and demonstrate a biological role for dnamediated charge transfer other awards include alan t waterman award of the national science foundation  first woman recipient fresenius award from phi lambda upsilon  first woman recipient eli lilly award in biological chemistry by the american chemical society  american chemical society award in pure chemistry  first woman recipient mayor of new yorks award in science and technology  american chemical society baekeland medal  first woman recipient fellow of the american academy of arts and sciences  macarthur foundation fellowship  garvan medal of the american chemical society  tolman award of the american chemical society  first woman recipient havinga medal  paul karrer gold medal  first woman recipient nichols medal of the american chemical society  first woman recipient weizmann women  science award  elected american philosophical society  elected national academy of sciences  ronald breslow award in biomimetic chemistry from the american chemical society  acs gibbs medal  fa cotton medal for excellence in chemical research of the american chemical society  national medal of science  fellow of the american chemical society acs  american institute of chemists gold medal  priestley medal  referencesedit  odom duncan t  the application of metallointercalators in recognition of and charge trasnport in nucleic acids caltechedu phd thesis california institute of technology oclc    a b c d e f g h i barton jacqueline k march   a career in chemistry chemical  engineering news   – retrieved  april    bernice segal  a professor of chemistry the new york times april   retrieved  april    a b c d e f g h i j ghaffari elizabeth  women leaders at work untold tales of women achieving their ambitions apress pp – isbn    the robert a welch foundation research bulletin houston texas robert a welch foundation   thompson clifford  current biography yearbook  th annual cumulation ed new york h w wilson p  isbn    jacqueline barton phd ’ and michael l lomax ma ’ to receive distinguished achievement awards at gsas convocation ceremonies graduate school of 